Introduction

This notebook outlines a solution to the exercise using the tidymodels package to implement the modeling. Also included is a brief exploratory data analysis. Three models are used: logistic regression; flexible discriminant analysis (FDA); and random forests. I have limited the number of models used and the size of the tuning grids to keep computation time low. The tidymodels framework easily allows for expansion of both if desired.

Exercise Instructions

Instructions adapted from Kuhn and Johnson (2013)1.

This exercise explores the direct marketing data of Larose (2006, Chap. 7)2. The goal of the original analysis was to predict which customers would respond to a promotional opportunity via mail. Of the 65,220 customers in the data set, 16.6% responded to the promotion. The predictors in the data set include

  • Spending habits, in aggregate and broken down by month and frequently visited store locations
  • The types of products purchased
  • Time between visits
  • Historical promotion response rates
  • Predefined customer cluster memberships

Larose (2006) discussed the class imbalance for this problem and demonstrates several techniques to achieve effective results.

  1. Read the data into R, conduct exploratory analyses, and determine the best method for encoding the predictors.
  2. Determine an appropriate split of the data and build several classification models for these data.
  3. Construct lift plots to understand a possible strategy regarding how many customers should be contacted to capture an estimated 60% of responders.
  4. Use sampling methods with several models. Do these models have better lift charts, and can they be used to contact fewer customers to achieve a 60 % response rate (of those who were given the promotion)?

df1

Fix Duplicate columns

There are 53 columns in this data set, but Larose (2006) mentions 51 variables. This means that there are two extra variables in this data set:

  1. The AVRG variable is the same as the Sales.per.Visit variable (allowing a small tolerance):
df1 %>% 
  select(AVRG, Sales.per.Visit) %>% 
  mutate(same = near(AVRG, Sales.per.Visit, tol = 0.01)) %>% 
  count(same)
  1. The Tot_Spend variable is the same as the MON variable (allowing a small tolerance):
df1 %>% 
  select(MON, Tot_Spend) %>% 
  mutate(same = near(MON, Tot_Spend, tol = 0.005)) %>% 
  count(same)

I will remove the Sales.per.Visit and Tot_Spend variables since they are duplicates.

Clean data

# Reload data:
df1 <- read.csv("/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter16/data/ClothingStore.txt")

# Remove duplicate variables:
df1 <- dplyr::select(df1, -Sales.per.Visit, -Tot_Spend)

# Remove variables with no information:
# (on page 272 of Larose (2006) the author recommends removing ZIP_CODE even though it could be used as a categorical variable)
df1 <- dplyr::select(df1, -HHKEY, -ZIP_CODE)

# Convert categorical and flag variable to factors:
df1 <- df1 %>% 
  mutate(CLUSTYPE = factor(CLUSTYPE),
         CC_CARD = factor(CC_CARD),
         VALPHON = factor(VALPHON),
         WEB = factor(WEB),
         RESP = factor(RESP))

# Round the negative percentages up to zero as per Larose (2006):
percent_vars <- c("PBLOUSES", "PCAR_PNTS", "PCAS_PNTS", "PDRESSES", "PFASHION", "PJACKETS", "PJEWELRY", "PKNIT_DRES", "PKNIT_TOPS", "PLEGWEAR", "POUTERWEAR", "PREVPD", "PSHIRTS", "PSUITS", "PSWEATERS")
df1 <- df1 %>% 
  mutate(across(all_of(percent_vars), ~if_else(.x < 0, 0, .x)))

For data splitting I will use a train/test split. For modeling I will use logistic regression, flexible discriminant analysis and random forests. I will use down- and up-sampling with all three of these models.

Data Splitting

Larose (2006) uses a 75%/25% training/test data split. I will do the same here.

set.seed(123)

# Initial split of the data into test set and non-test set:
n <- nrow(df1)
split1 <- initial_split(df1,
                        strata = RESP,
                        prop = 0.75)
df_train  <- training(split1) # this is the training set (21,600 rows)
df_test <- testing(split1) # this is the test set (7,199 rows)

# Create folds for CV using the training data:
# (only 5 folds are used for now to lower computation time)
folds <- vfold_cv(data = df_train, v = 5, strata = RESP)

Standard Modeling Methods

Logistic Regression

For preprocessing, I will convert the categorical variables to dummy variables. I will remove near-zero variance variables and highly correlated variables. I have also used KNN imputation for missing data. No resampling is required for this model. I will just fit() a model on the training data and make predictions on the test data.

Training set

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-   
  recipe(RESP ~ ., data = df_train) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors(), ) %>% 
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.8) %>% 
  step_knnimpute(all_predictors())
  
# Model
log_reg_mod1 <-
  logistic_reg() %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glm")

# Workflow
workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = log_reg_mod1) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1)

# Fit
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter16/objects/log_reg_fit_16.2.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  log_reg_fit <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  log_reg_fit <-
    workflow %>%
    fit(data = df_train)
  saveRDS(log_reg_fit, file1)
}

# View fit:
tidy(log_reg_fit)

Test set

# Fit final model on all of the training data and make predictions on the test set:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter16/objects/log_reg_final_fit_test_16.2.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  final_fit <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  final_fit <-
    workflow %>%
    last_fit(split1)
  saveRDS(final_fit, file1)
}

# Collect predictions:
test_results <- 
  final_fit %>%
  collect_predictions()
test_results$model <- "Logistic Regression"

Metrics, ROC curves, Gain curves

Gain curves (APM refers to them as lift curves) and ROC curves are plotted in this section. I us ethe gain curves to estimate the number of samples required to be tested to identify at least 60% of responders. I also look at the accuracy and sensitivity of the models.

Calculate Metrics

get_metrics <- function(test_results, model) {
  test_results <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }})
  
  metrics <- caret::confusionMatrix(data = test_results$.pred_class,
                                    reference = test_results$RESP,
                                    positive = "1")
  
  metrics$auc <- 
    test_results %>% 
    yardstick::roc_auc(RESP, .pred_1, event_level = "second") %>%
    pluck(".estimate")
  
  return(metrics)
}

models <- unique(test_results$model)
test_metrics <- map(models, ~get_metrics(test_results, .x)) %>% 
  set_names(models)

ROC Curves

# This function plots an ROC curve using the `yardstick` package:
plot_roc_curve <- function(test_results, model) {
  
  # Get AUC for labeling the plot:
  auc <- test_metrics[[{{ model }}]]$auc

  # ROC curve:
  p <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::roc_curve(RESP, .pred_1, event_level = "second") %>% 
    autoplot() +
    geom_label(aes(x = 0.75, y = 0.25, label = paste0("AUC:", round(auc, 3)))) +
    ggtitle(paste0("ROC - ", {{ model }}))
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = map(models, ~plot_roc_curve(test_results, .x)),
  nrow = 3
)

Gain Curves

# This function plots a gain curve using the `yardstick` package.
# I have included an option to include a "found" percentage with corresponding "tested" percentage
# marked on the plot.
plot_gain_curve <- function(test_results, model, percentage = NULL) {
  
  # Gain curve data:
  gain_data <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::gain_curve(RESP, .pred_1, event_level = "second")
  
  # If a percentage is supplied then find the corresponding "tested" percentage:
  if(!is.null(percentage)) {
    capture_percentage <- gain_data %>% 
      filter(.percent_found > percentage) %>% 
      head(1)
  }
  
  # Gain curve:
  p <- gain_data %>% 
    autoplot() +
    ggtitle(paste0("Gain - ", {{ model }}))
  
  if(!is.null(percentage)) {
    p <- p +
      geom_segment(data = capture_percentage, # vertical line
               aes(x = .percent_tested, xend = .percent_tested,
                   y = 0, yend = .percent_found),
               color = "indianred", linetype = "dashed") +
      geom_segment(data = capture_percentage, # horizontal line
                   aes(x = 0, xend = .percent_tested,
                       y = .percent_found, yend = .percent_found),
                   color = "indianred", linetype = "dashed") +
      geom_point(data = capture_percentage, aes(.percent_tested, .percent_found),
                 color = "indianred") +
      geom_label(data = capture_percentage,
                 aes(x = .percent_tested, .percent_found,
                     label = paste0(round(.percent_found, 1), "% Found at\n", round(.percent_tested, 1), "% Tested")),
                 hjust = 0, vjust = 1, nudge_x = 5) +
      scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(seq(0, 100, 25), round(capture_percentage$.percent_found, 1))) +
      coord_fixed(expand = F)
  }
  
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = map(models, ~plot_gain_curve(test_results, .x, percentage = 60)),
  nrow = 3
)

It seems that the models that use sampling have slightly better gain than the standard models. That is to say that fewer samples are required to be tested to capture at least 60% of responders.
